Read AGENTS.md and context/architecture-context.md, context/code-standards.md, and convex-server/AGENTS.md before starting.

We already have:

An Express server with MongoDB storing UserLog records (userId, repoName, repoOwner, commitId, action, status, timestamps).
A running Convex backend (daemon-doc-server) connected to the Express server via HTTP actions.
A working convex.service.js that can POST to Convex HTTP actions.

We need to create a shared logId field so that a UserLog record in MongoDB and its corresponding record in Convex DB can be linked by the client after fetching from both sources.

Requirements

MongoDB — UserLog Schema

Add a logId field to userLog.schema.js:

  logId: {
    type: String,
    required: true,
    unique: true,
    index: true,
  }

logId must be generated by the Express server at log creation time.
Use a UUID (crypto.randomUUID() — already available in Node 19+, no new dependency needed).
logId is written once at creation and never mutated.
logId is returned in every GET /api/logs response so the client can use it to correlate records.

Convex — logs Table

Add a logs table to convex-server/convex/schema.ts with the following fields:

  logs: defineTable({
    logId: v.string(),        // shared key — matches UserLog.logId in MongoDB
    userId: v.string(),
    repoName: v.string(),
    action: v.string(),
    status: v.string(),
    liveDetail: v.optional(v.string()),  // reserved for real-time detail messages
    updatedAt: v.number(),               // Unix ms timestamp, updated on every status change
  }).index("by_logId", ["logId"])
    .index("by_userId", ["userId"]),

Do not mirror all UserLog fields into Convex. Only store fields needed for real-time status tracking and client-side joining.

Convex — HTTP Actions

Add two new HTTP action endpoints to convex-server/convex/http.ts:

POST /api/logs/create
  Body: { logId, userId, repoName, action, status }
  Creates a new log document in the Convex logs table.
  Returns: { success: true, convexId: <_id> }

POST /api/logs/update
  Body: { logId, status, liveDetail? }
  Finds the document by logId index and patches status and updatedAt (and liveDetail if provided).
  Returns: { success: true }

Add corresponding Convex mutation functions in convex-server/convex/logs.ts.

Express — Log Creation and Update

In the existing worker/service layer where UserLog records are created and updated:

On UserLog creation:
  1. Generate logId = crypto.randomUUID()
  2. Save UserLog to MongoDB with logId
  3. Call convexFetch("/api/logs/create", { method: "POST", body: { logId, userId, repoName, action, status } })
     Fire-and-forget is acceptable — do not block the job pipeline on Convex write failures.
     Log a warning on failure but do not throw.

On UserLog status update (e.g. SUCCESS / FAILED):
  1. Call convexFetch("/api/logs/update", { method: "POST", body: { logId, status } })
     Same fire-and-forget pattern as above.

Architecture Rules

Do not change any existing Express route or MongoDB query that the client already calls.
logId is the only new field added to UserLog. Do not restructure the schema.
Convex is the real-time read layer; MongoDB is the authoritative source of truth.
The client joins the two datasets on logId client-side — no server-side join is required.
Keep Convex mutation logic thin: validate args, write to DB, return result.
Do not introduce TypeScript in the Express server. The convex-server project stays TypeScript.
Follow the fire-and-forget pattern for all Express → Convex writes to avoid coupling pipeline reliability to Convex availability.
